## Operator review checklist before send

- [ ] Recipient is the right person for the ask (cross-check against role table above)
- [ ] Subject line is direct and informative (no "Quick question" filler)
- [ ] If multiple asks, each has its own bullet and ideally a due date
- [ ] No external customer / sale-process content (internal coordination only)
- [ ] CC'd people genuinely need to be in the loop (not Cc-everyone reflex)
- [ ] Length 60–150 words
- [ ] Tone matches relationship (formal for Dwayne, casual for Ashley)

**Approved by**: ______________ **Date**: __________

---

## Anti-patterns

- ❌ **"Please assist with..."** — Maaz says "Could you handle...?" or "Can you..."
- ❌ **"Kindly do the needful"** — never; not Maaz's voice
- ❌ **All-team CC** — Maaz CCs deliberately. Not "everyone who's vaguely involved"
- ❌ **Internal email with formal signature block** — drop to just "Maaz" or "Maaz" + nothing else
- ❌ **Subject line "Update"** — be specific: "Q-Chem proposal status update"
- ❌ **Replying-all to broadcast threads with a 1-person comment** — start a new thread or reply direct

---

## Variant: heads-up vs ask

The body shape changes a lot based on whether you want action or just awareness:

**Heads-up (no action expected)**:
> "FYI — Aramco RTR May-31 review is now confirmed for 1am MT. Calendar invite incoming. No prep needed from your side; I'll handle the deck."

**Ask (specific action required)**:
> "Could you pull together a 1-pager on RTR project status by Thursday EOD? Need it for the May-31 review. Just bullet list of progress + next milestones; I'll style it."

Both are valid. Pick the right one — sending an "ask" framed as "heads-up" leads to missed work.

---

## Variant: bad-news internal email

When something has gone wrong (project slipped, customer is unhappy, sample run failed):

- Lead with the bad news (don't bury it)
- One sentence on what happened
- One sentence on what's being done now
- One ask (if any) — or "Will keep you posted; no action needed"
- Sign off: just "Maaz" (no warmth padding)

Example:
> "Heads-up — Q-Chem proposal slipped from Friday to Tuesday. Sanjay asked for two clarifications that need engineering input. Dharmesh is on it tomorrow morning. Will send the revised draft Tuesday by noon MT. — Maaz"
